            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf #AA">
                <p>The place of Andreas. Here lies...</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Il luogo di Andreas. Qui giace &#8230;</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The epitaph presents a structure peculiar to some Syracusan epitaphs that distinguish the owner of the burial place (in this case <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7944;&#957;&#948;&#961;&#941;&#945;&#962;</foreign>) from the deceased who is buried there (the name that was supposed to follow the expression <foreign xml:lang="grc">[&#7952;&#957;&#952;&#940;&#948;&#949; &#954;&#945;&#964;]&#945;&#954;&#949;&#8150;&#964;&#945;&#953;</foreign>): the form <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#954;&#945;&#964;&#945;&#954;&#949;&#8150;&#964;&#945;&#953;</foreign> is rare in Sicily but is also found in Catania in IG 14.559 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001378">ISic001378</ref>. Similarly, <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7956;&#957;&#952;&#945;</foreign> is rare in Sicily, which is why Korhonen&#8217;s supplement <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7952;&#957;&#952;&#940;&#948;&#949;</foreign> seems to be more likely here than Ferrua&#8217;s <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7956;&#957;&#952;&#945;</foreign>. The name of the deceased was probably to be read at l. 3 and in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-&#951;&#957;&#953;&#959;&#962;</foreign> (probable names are <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#925;&#949;&#956;&#942;&#957;&#953;&#959;&#962;</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#925;&#949;&#959;&#956;&#942;&#957;&#953;&#959;&#962;</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#925;&#959;&#965;&#956;&#942;&#957;&#953;&#959;&#962;</foreign>, which are attested in Sicily, see LGPN 3A: 312-313, 330): this would leave space in the line, although the name of the deceased could also have been in a centred position.</p>
            </div>
